	<!-- Character Art -->
	
	<section id="CA" class="section">
	  <h2>Character Art</h2>
	  <p>Character Art from Concept to 3D</p>
	  <br>
	  <div class="image-thumbnails">
		<img src="pPort/FSM/Concept.png" alt="Polipus 2D Concept Art" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/CA/polipusRetop.png" alt="Polipus Retopology" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/CA/polipusTile.png" alt="Polipus Texture Tile" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/CA/vertexPaint.png" alt="Polipus Vertex Paint" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/FSM/polipusicons.png" alt="Polipus Final" class="thumbnail">
	  </div>

	  <p>Designing the Polipus character presented a unique challenge. I combined vertex painting
	  and a texture tile to add depth and dimension to the low-poly model. The most challenging aspect
	  was unwrapping the model to effectively utilize vertex painting. This technique allowed me to
	  introduce subtle shadows and highlights without modifying the base texture itself.</p>
	  <br>
	  <br>
	  <div class="image-thumbnails">
		<img src="pPort/CA/dti.png" alt="Officer T Pose Textured" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/CA/dtiEdit.PNG" alt="Officer Poly" class="thumbnail">
	  </div>
	  
	  <p>Creating a humanoid character for Pirate Radio Stealth Rave presented several challenges. 
	  To achieve a low-poly aesthetic reminiscent of the PlayStation 1 era, I carefully designed 
	  the officer model to minimize the polygon count while maintaining visual appeal.</p>
	  <br>
	  <br>
	</section>
	
	<!-- Substance Paint -->
	
	<section id="SubP" class="section">
	  <h2>Substance Painter</h2>
	  <p>The process of the tree stump from Blender to Substance Painter.</p>
	  <br>
	  <div class="image-thumbnails">
		<img src="pPort/SubP/stumpBlockout.png" alt="Tree stump blockout" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/SubP/stumpSculpt.png" alt="Sculpt for the shape" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/SubP/stumpUV.png" alt="UV Unwrap and package" class="thumbnail">
	  </div>

	  <p>Creating the low and high poly tree stump model. Starting with the blockout, 
	  I remeshed the model to increase the face count so I could sculpt the shape. 
	  I faced some challeneges unwrapping the UV but overcame them by marking seams to help with the unpacking process.</p>
	  <br>
	  <br>
	  <div class="image-thumbnails">
		<img src="pPort/SubP/highPolyNormalSculpt.png" alt="Tree stump blockout" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/SubP/CapturenormalMapBakingonLowpoly.png" alt="Sculpt for the shape" class="thumbnail">
	  </div>
	  
	  <p>Sculpting further detail on a seperate model, once I was happy with the result 
	  the details were baked to a normal map for the low poly version of the model. This was done to help add depth and detail
	  to the lower poly model and to help create a guide for Substance Painter during the baked lighting step.</p>
	  <br>
	  <br>
	  
	  
	  <div class="image-thumbnails">
		<img src="pPort/SubP/generators.png" alt="Tree stump blockout" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/SubP/inspect.png" alt="Sculpt for the shape" class="thumbnail">
		<img src="pPort/SubP/CapturebeforeHandpainttouches.png" alt="Sculpt for the shape" class="thumbnail">
	  </div>
	  <p>Importing the model into Substance Painter, I created a base material for the colour, metal and rough.
	  Then added additonal layers to generate some highlights and baked lighting for the normal map.
	  <br>After I was happy with the generators, I went in the paint tool to create some human decisions 
	  and to add further hue changes and depth where I saw fit.</p>
	  <br>
	  <br>
	  
	</section>
	
